The streame, springs, and wells were pro· tected from pollution by orders made at the court. In East Rainton (p. 146) the bailiff is ordered to arrest those who place their plough-irone in the spring. At a subsequcnt court the tenants are ordered to make a pond nigh the spring for cooling their plough-irone, so asto preserve it from pollution. In the adjoining vill of West Rainton the tenants are forbidden to use the common well for washing clothes and other things. Similar orders are made at Westoe against so using Holaw-Pool, reserved for watoring cattle and domestic purposes, and also a watercourse nigh the chapel (pp. 38, 160). 'lhe community of the vill of N ether-Heworth appear to have appointed the Smithburn for brewing and making broad, and its use for washing is forbidden.
